{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>Bacterial flagella are responsible for motility and chemotaxis [[cite:PUB00002583]]. They comprise a basal body, a hook and a filament, the latter accounting for 98% of the mass [[cite:PUB00002080]]. Flagellin is the subunit protein that polymerises to form the flagella [[cite:PUB00002058]], the subunits being transported through the centre of the filament to the tip, where they then polymerise [[cite:PUB00002583]]. Both the N- and C- termini of the subunit protein, which are Î±-helical in structure [[cite:PUB00002583]], are required to mediate polymerisation. Although no export or assembly, consensus sequences have been identified: Ala, Val, Leu, Ile, Gly, Ser, Thr, Asn, Gln and Asp tend to make up around 90% of the sequence, Cys and Trp being absent [[cite:PUB00002080]].</p>\n\n<p>Flagellin plays a role in the activation of innate and adaptive immunity. It is an specific ligand for Toll-like receptor 5 (TLR5) in the host, which has lead to great interest to use it as adjuvant for vaccines [[cite:PUB00099953], [cite:PUB00099952], [cite:PUB00099954]]. The protein is also recognised by the intracellular NAIP5/NLRC4 inflammasome receptor [[cite:PUB00099955]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure {"accession" "4cfi", "name" "3D structure of FliC from Burkholderia pseudomallei"}, :overlaps-with nil, :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR42792" "FLAGELLIN"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "Flagellin", "short" "Flagellin"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 64, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 4471, "taxa" 18352, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 63388, "sets" 0, "proteins" 63388, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 49221}, "pathways" 8}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {}, :set-info nil, :accession "IPR001492", :literature {"PUB00002058" {"URL" nil, "issue" "3", "authors" ["Kuwajima G" "Asaka J" "